    36	
    37	## Recommended Topics
    38	
    39	| Topic | Type | Direction | Status | Purpose |
    40	| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
    41	| `/uav/target_position` | `geometry_msgs/msg/Point` | client -> UAV bridge | Implemented in `uav_control_bridge`; Demo 04 example also subscribes | Position-only target in local NED. |
    42	| `/uav/target_pose` | `geometry_msgs/msg/PoseStamped` | client -> UAV bridge | Future | Position plus desired yaw. Roll and pitch should be ignored by the bridge. |
    43	| `/uav/current_position` | `geometry_msgs/msg/PointStamped` | UAV bridge -> clients | Implemented in `uav_control_bridge` | Current filtered local NED position. |
    44	| `/uav/current_target` | `geometry_msgs/msg/PointStamped` | UAV bridge -> clients | Implemented in `uav_control_bridge` | Sanitized target currently being sent to PX4. |
    45	| `/uav/reached_target` | `std_msgs/msg/Bool` | UAV bridge -> clients | Implemented in `uav_control_bridge` | `true` when the current target is reached within configured tolerances. |
    46	| `/uav/control_state` | `std_msgs/msg/String` | UAV bridge -> clients | Implemented in `uav_control_bridge` | Human-readable control state such as `TRACKING`, `HOLDING`, or `INVALID_TARGET`. |
    47	| `/uav/emergency_stop` | `std_msgs/msg/Bool` | client -> UAV bridge | Future | `true` requests an immediate safety stop action. |
    48	
    49	## Topic Details
    50	
    51	### `/uav/target_position`
    52	
    53	Type: `geometry_msgs/msg/Point`
    54	
    55	Fields:
    56	
    57	| Field | Meaning |
    58	| --- | --- |
    59	| `x` | Target north position in local NED, meters. |
    60	| `y` | Target east position in local NED, meters. |
    61	| `z` | Target down position in local NED, meters. Use `z=-altitude` for positive height commands. |
    62	
    63	This topic is the minimal high-level command surface. It is suitable for simple
    64	vision trackers, scripted waypoint tests, and LeRobot policies that only need to
    65	move the UAV platform to a local position.
    66	
    67	The `uav_control_bridge` node subscribes to this topic, rejects invalid or
    68	unsafe NED points, and forwards only the last safe target as a PX4 position
    69	setpoint through the shared offboard base class. Demo 04 still subscribes to
    70	this topic as a direct external setpoint example.
    71	
    72	### `/uav/target_pose`
    73	
    74	Type: `geometry_msgs/msg/PoseStamped`
    75	
    76	Recommended usage:
    77	
    78	- `header.frame_id`: `uav_local_ned`
    79	- `pose.position.x/y/z`: local NED target position.
    80	- `pose.orientation`: desired yaw only. The bridge should extract yaw and ignore
    81	  commanded roll/pitch so high-level clients cannot fight the flight controller.
    82	
    83	Use this topic when a module needs to control the UAV heading, camera direction,
    84	or approach orientation. If both `/uav/target_pose` and
    85	`/uav/target_position` are active, the bridge should define one priority rule,
    86	for example "latest valid command wins" or "pose has priority".
    87	
    88	### `/uav/current_position`
    89	
    90	Type: `geometry_msgs/msg/PointStamped`
    91	
    92	The bridge publishes the current vehicle local position after checking PX4
    93	validity flags. Source data comes from:
    94	
    95	```text
    96	/fmu/out/vehicle_local_position_v1
    97	```
    98	
    99	Mapping:
   100	
   101	```text
   102	point.x = VehicleLocalPosition.x
   103	point.y = VehicleLocalPosition.y
   104	point.z = VehicleLocalPosition.z
   105	```
   106	
   107	The bridge only publishes this topic when both `xy_valid` and `z_valid` are
   108	true. The `header.frame_id` is `uav_local_ned`.
   109	
   110	Clients that need positive altitude should compute `altitude=-point.z`.
   111	
   112	### `/uav/current_target`
   113	
   114	Type: `geometry_msgs/msg/PointStamped`
   115	
   116	Publish the target after validation. This may differ from the raw
   117	`/uav/target_position` or `/uav/target_pose` command when a client requests an
   118	unsafe or too-large jump because the bridge keeps holding the last safe target.
   119	The `header.frame_id` is `uav_local_ned`.
   120	
   121	### `/uav/reached_target`
   122	
   123	Type: `std_msgs/msg/Bool`
   124	
   125	Implemented bridge logic:
   126	
   127	```text
   128	true when horizontal_error <= 0.30 m
   129	and vertical_error <= 0.20 m
   130	for at least 1.0 s
   131	```
   132	
   133	The exact tolerances are parameters on `uav_control_bridge`:
   134	
   135	| Parameter | Default |
   136	| --- | --- |
   137	| `reach_xy_tolerance` | `0.30` |
   138	| `reach_z_tolerance` | `0.20` |
   139	| `reach_hold_time` | `1.0` |
   140	
   190	
   191	Positive altitude values are not accepted directly on `/uav/target_position`.
   192	Clients must convert to NED before publishing:
   193	
   194	```text
   195	TrajectorySetpoint.position = [north_m, east_m, -altitude_m]
   196	```
   197	
   198	The bridge must keep publishing `px4_msgs/msg/OffboardControlMode` with
   199	`position=true` at the required offboard rate while streaming trajectory
   200	setpoints.
   201	
   202	## Safety Limits
   203	
   204	Initial simulation defaults should be conservative and parameterized:
   205	
   206	| Limit | Recommended default | Behavior |
   207	| --- | --- | --- |
   208	| Maximum altitude | `5.0 m` | Reject or clamp commands with `z < -5.0`. |
   209	| Minimum altitude | `0.5 m` while airborne | Reject commands too close to the ground unless landing mode is active. |
   210	| Maximum horizontal range | `5.0 m` radius from local origin | Reject or clamp commands where `sqrt(x*x + y*y) > 5.0`. |
   211	| Maximum horizontal speed | `2.0 m/s` commanded slew | Rate-limit target movement before publishing to PX4. |
   212	| Maximum vertical speed | `1.0 m/s` commanded slew | Rate-limit changes in NED `z`. |
   213	| Target jump limit | `1.5 m` per received command | Split larger jumps into intermediate setpoints or reject them. |
   214	| Target timeout | `1.0 s` for streaming clients | Hold last safe target when command input expires. |
   215	
   216	The current `uav_control_bridge` rejects commands outside these altitude, range,
   217	and target-jump limits. On target timeout it keeps publishing the last safe
   218	target and rate-limits timeout warnings to no more than once per timeout
   219	interval. It publishes the held safe target on `/uav/current_target` and the
   220	state on `/uav/control_state`. It also publishes `/uav/current_position` from
   221	valid PX4 local-position samples and `/uav/reached_target` using the configured
   222	reach tolerances.
   223	
   224	## Why LeRobot Should Not Publish `/fmu/in/*`
   225	
   226	LeRobot, vision modules, and task planners should not publish PX4 input topics
   227	directly because those topics are low-level flight-control interfaces:
   228	
   229	- `/fmu/in/trajectory_setpoint` expects PX4 NED semantics, valid timestamps,
   230	  feasible setpoints, and continuous streaming.
   231	- `/fmu/in/offboard_control_mode` must be synchronized with setpoint streaming
   232	  for PX4 offboard mode to remain valid.
   233	- `/fmu/in/vehicle_command` can arm, change modes, or land the vehicle.
   234	- Direct publishers can bypass altitude, range, speed, timeout, and emergency
   235	  stop checks.
   236	- Multiple direct publishers can race and send conflicting setpoints.
   237	
   238	The high-level `/uav/*` API gives learning and perception modules a small,
   239	auditable command surface. A single bridge node can validate commands, enforce
   240	limits, publish state, and own the PX4-specific details.
   241	
   242	## Future Integration
   243	
   244	### Vision Module
   245	
   246	A visual tracker should publish object-relative or world-local targets through
   247	`/uav/target_position` after transforming detections into the local NED frame.
   248	It should subscribe to `/uav/current_position`, `/uav/current_target`, and
   249	`/uav/control_state` for feedback and should stop commanding motion when the
   250	bridge reports `E_STOP`, `LANDING`, or `INVALID_TARGET`.
   251	
   252	### LeRobot Policy
   253	
   254	LeRobot should output high-level goals such as "move the UAV platform to this
   255	local target" or "hold while the arm acts". Those goals should be translated to
   256	`/uav/target_position` or `/uav/target_pose`. LeRobot must not control PX4
   257	motors, attitude, arming, or offboard internals directly.
   258	
   259	### UAV Arm
   260	
   261	For the simplified 2-DOF or 3-DOF arm simulation, keep the flight platform and
   262	arm policies separated:
   263	
   264	- PX4/offboard bridge keeps the UAV stable using `/uav/*` targets.
   265	- Arm controller handles local joint or end-effector commands.
   266	- Task planner coordinates phases: fly near target, hold position, move arm,
   267	  then retreat.
   268	
   269	The planner can use `/uav/reached_target` and `/uav/control_state` as gates
   270	before enabling arm actions.
   271	
   272	## Implementation Notes
   273	
   274	Implemented in `uav_control_bridge`:
   275	
   276	- Subscribe to `/uav/target_position` as `geometry_msgs/msg/Point` in local NED.
   277	- Subscribe to `/fmu/out/vehicle_local_position_v1` as
   278	  `px4_msgs/msg/VehicleLocalPosition`.
   279	- Publish PX4 offboard mode, trajectory setpoint, and vehicle command messages
   280	  only through `OffboardPositionControl`.
   281	- Publish `/uav/current_position`, `/uav/current_target`,
   282	  `/uav/reached_target`, and `/uav/control_state`.
   283	- Reject non-finite, positive-altitude, out-of-altitude-limit,
   284	  out-of-horizontal-range, and excessive-jump targets.
   285	- Hold the last safe target on timeout.
   286	- Report `TRACKING`, `REACHED`, `HOLDING`, and `INVALID_TARGET` bridge states.
   287	
   288	Interfaces still needing implementation:
   289	
   290	- Subscribe to `/uav/target_pose`.
   291	- Subscribe to `/uav/emergency_stop`.
   292	- Add validation, clamping, and slew limiting in the future UAV bridge.
   293	
   294	Do not implement these by changing PX4-Autopilot. They belong in the custom ROS
   295	2 workspace package, likely as an extension or replacement for the current Demo
   296	04 external setpoint node.

